title: WTS/WTT .223 AMMO Hornady and Wolf
postcontent:
I have two types of ammo for sale.
The first I have is Hornady .223. This is the TAP training ammo. It works perfect in my AR-15 (bushy). I have bout alot of this stuff, and it is what I Shoot most. I have some extra boxes, and need to rearrange the gun collection. I have put aside 200 rounds for sell, each in 50rd boxes. This ammo has worked well in my standard bushy 16" patrolman barrel.

I am asking for $25/box of 50 rounds, or take the whole 4 boxes for $85



The second ammo I am selling is Wolf. You know this ammo... This ammo has given me much pain over the past year. It started when my buddy bought a bunch of wolf, and it ran flawless in his rifle. I was there, saw him shoot a couple hundred rounds of it, and listening to him say how much he saved by buying this stuff. So, going against what I usually do (buy the best I can afford) I bought 200 rounds of Wolf. My bushy hates it. I get a failure to feed every mag or two. I get about 3+ jams per beta-mag. This isn't acceptable to me. But that was my rifle. Like I said, my buddy's rifle ate it up. I've seen Oly AR15's shoot this without issue at the range. Something about my rifle hates it. I know a bunch of people on AR15.com who swear by this stuff, and it sells. Gander has raised their price on this ammo considerably. Don't buy it from Gander though, I'll sell you the rest of this ammo I have, 50 rounds loose for $18. They were previously loaded in Pmags, but I have taken them out and counted them. 
You can count for yourself if you are interested. I know this rifle works for some people, just not me. This is the new stuff by the way, not the corrisive Wolf. I've always stayed away from corrosive ammo.

50 rounds/$18 




I am in the Fishers area, but Frequent Avon and Indianapolis.

I am interested in this for trade:
38spl ammo
9mm, anything other that 115gr.
12ga ammo.
Glock Magazines (I have a 9mm and a 40)
AR15 Magazines

Email me with all offers.

title: Very Nice Springfield M1 Garand
postcontent:
I hate to let her go but I need the cash.
Its a 58 Mil Springfield with a unique USGI Marlin Barrel. From what I have gathered Marlin barrels were used for awhile on SA Garands when SA was having trouble with their barrels. Later Marlins were used a replacement barrels which I believe this is.
Stock has very nice graining with a few dings and small gouges, no cracks. Handgaurds are in same condition.
No stampings on the USGI stock ,which is normal for a arsenal replacement 
Has National Match Op Rod, remainder of parts are a assortment of Springfield parts
There is some wear to the parkerizing on the edges or corners and to the gas cylinder as expected from use. Absolutly no rust or pitting .
I have completely stripped the rifle ,cleaned and greased, replaced Op Rod spring and clip ejector spring.
Rifle functions perfectly. I have collected Garands for years and have inspected this one and know it to be clear and free of any problems
Barrel is next to new with a Muzzle Wear of less than one. It measures .50 on my gauge. Couldnt have very many rds through it since the rebarrel.
I bought this rifle from a private owner so I dont know the history behind it. It is not a Import and could have come from CMP at one time
Nothing CMP has now compares to this Garand as far as condition of the barrel. Nothing they offer has this low barrrel wear unless you get a new commercial barrel
This is a very nice Garand, you would have a hard time finding one as nice as this and with a barrel with such little wear
If you want a Garand that is mechanically perfect this is it,. It will be a great shooter for you and whoever you pass it down to.
It needs nothing but ammo I may be able to help in that department also.

Price is $900.00 cash, price is firm, no trades. Must have valid Ohio ID , and be legally able to own firearms
If you need more pics or info just ask

title: S&W 22A target pistol
postcontent:
Caliber - .22LR
Barrel length - 7"
Magazine capacity - 10 rounds

This is a heavy barrel target pistol. The sights are adjustable and the barrel rib is also a rail for mounting optics.  Pistol is in good shape, I fired it very little. The recoil spring is new - the original one flew off to parts unknown during cleaning.

The pistol works well, but has trouble with some of the cheap bulk pack ammo. Occasionally a cartridge would be underloaded and the slide does not go back far enough to get the momentum to snap the extractor over the rim. Using high velocity or better quality ammo fixes this problem.

The pistol comes with factory case, three magazines, manual, and a chamber flag.

I would like to see a valid Permit To Purchase or a Permit To Carry (that means it has a current photo ID with it) and will write up a bill of sale on request.

title: WTS Mauser HSC .380 w/(2)mags+holster
postcontent:
I bought this gun with the idea of gifting it to my mother as a carry/purse gun. She is not strong enough (4'11" 90lbs) to pull back the slide with comfort. I purchased this firearm earlier this year from the estate of an retired WPD police Captain. I was told by his family that this was purchased new sometime in the late 70's and if it had 3-4 boxes fired they would be surprised. This gun was stored in the officers personal vehicle much of its life until one day the youngest boy took it out of the glove box and proceeded to shoot a hole in the floor of his father's new truck. I was told from then on it was stored away inside the home until I purchased. I am selling this for what I purchased it for and that is $330. I have seen these listed local and on the internet anywhere from $295 in poor condition to $475 super nice like new. I think my asking price is very fair. This firearm comes with a holster and 2 magazines which are both factory Mauser. Firearm has very little wear if any of inner workings and barrel. Holster and storage wear as would be expected for a firearm 30+ years in age. Would make a nice small/mid carry firearm for someone. I would be interested in trades towards what might fit my mothers needs or something I desire which at this time would be something chambered in .44/.357 or a Glock product. 

Last photo for size comparison. Glock 17 full size 9mm and FIE pocket .25

title: Misc bow hunting gear
postcontent:
most of this is stuff that i won in an auction lot, I'll never use it.

Bowbug - this is a game tracking device.  You put a little pronged transmitter on your arrow and then you can locate your game via radio transmission.  legal in oklahoma.

SSI Hearing enhancement - this is basically a hearing aid type thing that is supposed to heighten your hearing when in the field.

Trophy Taker Drop Arrow Rest

Youth Winn release, left handed - I'm not a left handed child, but if you are this is a good release to have.

String Tracker - Also used for tracking game after a shot, this one threads a brightly colored string through your animal and leaves a path to your game

make me an offer on this stuff.  Don't forget I'm actually in Lawton, not OKC.
-Luke

title: 1943 Iz. M91/30 PU sniper rifle
postcontent:
Beautiful restored "REAL" Russian 1943 Izhevsk M91/30 PU sniper rifle - in very excellent condition throughout. All matching stamped numbers - NO lineout/restamps or e/p. All Izhevsk marked metal parts. Original scope number is deep stamped on barrel shank, has not been "scrubbed". Unusual fingerjointed stock with clear sharp markings and excellent condition shellac finish. Bore shows typical frosting in grooves but strong lands from chamber to crown - NOT counterbored - rifle was a great shooter prior to restoration, has not been fired since completion. WW2 dated SVT type scope, "refurb" marked with genuine post war Soviet mount / leather lens caps / canvas cover / arsenal record papers. Reproduction "Accumounts" steel base plate mounted in original receiver screw and pin holes; reproduction correct style "bent handle bolt" from Jim Robert "The Boltman". Sale includes "original" refurb force matched straight handle bolt body, sling/bayonet/ammo pouch/oil can and complete tool kit in roll up pouch, also 40 rnds of Czech silvertip LB ammo.
$650.00 for all.

title: Vulcan Armament V-50 .50 BMG single-shot rifle
postcontent:
Up for sale is a BRAND NEW Vulcan Armament V-50. The V50SS-300 rifle features a massive SAE 4150 receiver and a three lug bolt with a 60-degree bolt throw, cock on opening action, a shell holder type extractor for absolutely positive extraction, and a machined aircraft grade aluminum stock. The barrel is machined from ordnance grade, chrome moly, high vanadium steel hardened to Rc 28-32. The barrel is 30" long, has 8 grooves, 1-15" right hand twist and features a SAAMI spec chamber which will allow the use of any SAAMI spec ammo. The barrel and all external steel parts, are manganese phosphate finished for long lasting good looks and corrosion protection. The V50SS utilizes the time proven standard, '98 Mauser trigger system for absolute safety. This rifle also features a high efficiency "shark fin" muzzle break, machined from solid bar stock and threaded on to the muzzle of the barrel with 1-12 TPI threads. This muzzle break is designed to reduce felt recoil to that of a 12 ga. Shotgun. The muzzle break can be "Tuned" to the barrel by altering the length via the long thread shank. This feature allows the operator to find the "sweet spot" for the break that gives the best accuracy. An M1913 Picatinny scope rail is attached via oversized grade 8 allen screws for easy mounting of optics. The oversized recoil shoulder distributes the recoil over a large surface area affording rock solid mounting to the stock. The bolt has three huge locking surfaces and a 60 degree throw. It features a "primary extraction" cam for positive extraction of the case. The receiver is machined from bar stock SAE 4150 steel and features pressure release vents for BOTH case separation and primer pierce, making this one of the strongest, safest actions available. We have tested these actions and bolts to pressures exceeding 100,000 psi with no evidence of failure. The stock is machined from aircraft aluminum bar stock. This stock is made to machine tool tolerances and is completely impervious to climate and temperature. It is attached to an aluminum buttstock with a shock absorbing recoil to further reduce felt recoil and allow the shooter to comfortably shoot all day. A bipod mounting rod is threaded into the stock, securing the oversized recoil shoulder and locking the recoil shoulder to the stock for increased accuracy. The Specs on the rifle are: Overall Length: 52" / 1321mm
Barrel Length: 30" / 762mm
Barrel Twist: 1-15" / 1/381mm, RH, 8 groove
Weight: 30.0 Lbs / 13.6 kg
Recoil: 19 ft/lbs / 2.62 kg/m / 25.7 Joules
 21 Years or older to bid please. Postal Money Orders or Cashier's checks only. NO CA SALES. This will ship to me from my distributor upon receiving payment.
